Actually, Poland tried to be very science-oriented,. especially in the 70s and 80s. Propaganda underscored how many universities, science academies and research institutes we had, and those places actually tried to do proper research. Only disciplines directly linked to the regime's ideology suffered from systemic faults - economics, for example. The biggest problem was lack of funding. By the 1980s Poland was in a deep crisis, caused partly by overspending in the previous decade. We were 20 or more years behind the West, but not for lack of trying.

The Polish autocracy pre-1989 was very much unlike what you think it was (methinks). Many of the government's agendas were actually very progressive, and oppression was minimal by Eastern Bloc standards (especially compared to the GDR, say). Much of what's going on in the US now would be shocking to Polish people from 40 years ago.

